AllQueryStringTypes.name: AllQueryStringTypes
AllQueryStringTypes.documentation: This example uses all query string types.

ConstantAndVariableQueryString.name: ConstantAndVariableQueryString
ConstantAndVariableQueryString.documentation: This example uses fixed query string params and variable query string params. The fixed query string parameters and variable parameters must both be serialized (implementations may need to merge them together).

ConstantQueryString.name: ConstantQueryString
ConstantQueryString.documentation: This example uses a constant query string parameters and a label. This simply tests that labels and query string parameters are compatible. The fixed query string parameter named "hello" should in no way conflict with the label, {hello}.

ContentTypeParameters.name: ContentTypeParameters
ContentTypeParameters.documentation: The example tests how servers must support requests containing a Content-Type header with parameters.

DocumentType.name: DocumentType
DocumentType.documentation: This example serializes a document as part of the payload.

DocumentTypeAsMapValue.name: DocumentTypeAsMapValue
DocumentTypeAsMapValue.documentation: This example serializes documents as the value of maps.

DocumentTypeAsPayload.name: DocumentTypeAsPayload
DocumentTypeAsPayload.documentation: This example serializes a document as the entire HTTP payload.

EmptyInputAndEmptyOutput.name: EmptyInputAndEmptyOutput
EmptyInputAndEmptyOutput.documentation: The example tests how requests and responses are serialized when there's no request or response payload because the operation has an empty input and empty output structure that reuses the same shape. While this should be rare, code generators must support this.

GreetingWithErrors.name: GreetingWithErrors
GreetingWithErrors.documentation:
This operation has four possible return values:

  1. A successful response in the form of GreetingWithErrorsOutput
  2. An InvalidGreeting error.
  3. A BadRequest error.
  4. A FooError.

Implementations must be able to successfully take a response and properly (de)serialize successful and error responses based on the the presence of the

HttpEmptyPrefixHeaders.name: HttpEmptyPrefixHeaders
HttpEmptyPrefixHeaders.documentation: Clients that perform this test extract all headers from the response.

HttpPayloadTraits.name: HttpPayloadTraits
HttpPayloadTraits.documentation:
This example serializes a blob shape in the payload.

In this example, no JSON document is synthesized because the payload is not a structure or a union type.

HttpPayloadWithStructure.name: HttpPayloadWithStructure
HttpPayloadWithStructure.documentation:
This example serializes a structure in the payload.

Note that serializing a structure changes the wrapper element name to match the targeted structure.

HttpPayloadWithUnion.name: HttpPayloadWithUnion
HttpPayloadWithUnion.documentation: This example serializes a union in the payload.

HttpPrefixHeaders.name: HttpPrefixHeaders
HttpPrefixHeaders.documentation: This examples adds headers to the input of a request and response by prefix.

HttpPrefixHeadersInResponse.name: HttpPrefixHeadersInResponse
HttpPrefixHeadersInResponse.documentation: Clients that perform this test extract all headers from the response.

HttpRequestWithLabels.name: HttpRequestWithLabels
HttpRequestWithLabels.documentation: The example tests how requests are serialized when there's no input payload but there are HTTP labels.

HttpRequestWithLabelsAndTimestampFormat.name: HttpRequestWithLabelsAndTimestampFormat
HttpRequestWithLabelsAndTimestampFormat.documentation: The example tests how requests serialize different timestamp formats in the URI path.

IgnoreQueryParamsInResponse.name: IgnoreQueryParamsInResponse
IgnoreQueryParamsInResponse.documentation: This example ensures that query string bound request parameters are serialized in the body of responses if the structure is used in both the request and response.

InputAndOutputWithHeaders.name: InputAndOutputWithHeaders
InputAndOutputWithHeaders.documentation: The example tests how requests and responses are serialized when there is no input or output payload but there are HTTP header bindings.

JsonEnums.name: JsonEnums
JsonEnums.documentation: This example serializes enums as top level properties, in lists, sets, and maps.

JsonIntEnums.name: JsonIntEnums
JsonIntEnums.documentation: This example serializes intEnums as top level properties, in lists, sets, and maps.

JsonLists.name: JsonLists
JsonLists.documentation:
This test case serializes JSON lists for the following cases for both input and output:

  1. Normal JSON lists.
  2. Normal JSON sets.
  3. JSON lists of lists.
  4. Lists of structures.

JsonTimestamps.name: JsonTimestamps
JsonTimestamps.documentation: This tests how timestamps are serialized, including using the default format of date-time and various @timestampFormat trait values.

JsonUnions.name: JsonUnions
JsonUnions.documentation: This operation uses unions for inputs and outputs.

MediaTypeHeader.name: MediaTypeHeader
MediaTypeHeader.documentation: This example ensures that mediaType strings are base64 encoded in headers.

NoInputAndNoOutput.name: NoInputAndNoOutput
NoInputAndNoOutput.documentation: The example tests how requests and responses are serialized when there's no request or response payload because the operation has no input or output. While this should be rare, code generators must support this.

NoInputAndOutput.name: NoInputAndOutput
NoInputAndOutput.documentation: The example tests how requests and responses are serialized when there's no request or response payload because the operation has no input and the output is empty. While this should be rare, code generators must support this.

NullAndEmptyHeadersClient.name: NullAndEmptyHeadersClient
NullAndEmptyHeadersClient.documentation: Null headers are not sent over the wire, empty headers are serialized to ""

NullAndEmptyHeadersServer.name: NullAndEmptyHeadersServer
NullAndEmptyHeadersServer.documentation: Null headers are not sent over the wire, empty headers are serialized to ""

OmitsNullSerializesEmptyString.name: OmitsNullSerializesEmptyString
OmitsNullSerializesEmptyString.documentation: Omits null, but serializes empty string value.

OmitsSerializingEmptyLists.name: OmitsSerializingEmptyLists
OmitsSerializingEmptyLists.documentation: Omits serializing empty lists. Because empty strings are serilized as Foo=, empty lists cannot also be serialized as Foo= and instead must be omitted.

PostUnionWithJsonName.name: PostUnionWithJsonName
PostUnionWithJsonName.documentation: This operation defines a union that uses jsonName on some members.

TestBodyStructure.name: TestBodyStructure
TestBodyStructure.documentation:
This example operation serializes a structure in the HTTP body.

It should ensure Content-Type: application/json is used in all requests and that an "empty" body is an empty JSON document ({}).

TestGetNoInputNoPayload.name: TestGetNoInputNoPayload
TestGetNoInputNoPayload.documentation:
This example GET operation has no input and serializes a request without a HTTP body.

These tests are to ensure we do not attach a body or related headers (Content-Length, Content-Type) to operations that semantically cannot produce an HTTP body.

TestGetNoPayload.name: TestGetNoPayload
TestGetNoPayload.documentation:
This example GET operation serializes a request without a modeled HTTP body.

These tests are to ensure we do not attach a body or related headers (Content-Length, Content-Type) to operations that semantically cannot produce an HTTP body.

TestPayloadBlob.name: TestPayloadBlob
TestPayloadBlob.documentation:
This example operation serializes a payload targeting a blob.

The Blob shape is not structured content and we cannot make assumptions about what data will be sent. This test ensures only a generic "Content-Type: application/octet-stream" header is used, and that we are not treating an empty body as an empty JSON document.

TestPayloadStructure.name: TestPayloadStructure
TestPayloadStructure.documentation:
This example operation serializes a payload targeting a structure.

This enforces the same requirements as TestBodyStructure but with the body specified by the @httpPayload trait.

TestPostNoInputNoPayload.name: TestPostNoInputNoPayload
TestPostNoInputNoPayload.documentation:
This example POST operation has no input and serializes a request without a HTTP body.

These tests are to ensure we do not attach a body or related headers (Content-Type) to a POST operation with no modeled input.

TestPostNoPayload.name: TestPostNoPayload
TestPostNoPayload.documentation:
This example POST operation serializes a request without a modeled HTTP body.

These tests are to ensure we do not attach a body or related headers (Content-Type) to a POST operation with no modeled payload.

TimestampFormatHeaders.name: TimestampFormatHeaders
TimestampFormatHeaders.documentation: This example tests how timestamp request and response headers are serialized.

UnitInputAndOutput.name: UnitInputAndOutput
UnitInputAndOutput.documentation: This test is similar to NoInputAndNoOutput, but uses explicit Unit types.

ComplexError.documentation: This error is thrown when a request is invalid.

FooError.documentation: This error has test cases that test some of the dark corners of Amazon service framework history. It should only be implemented by clients.

boolean.documentation: Serialized in the path as true or false.

timestamp.documentation: Note that this member has no format, so it's serialized as an RFC 3399 date-time.

InvalidGreeting.documentation: This error is thrown when an invalid greeting value is provided.

MyUnion.documentation: A union with a representative set of types for members.

UnionInputOutput.documentation: A shared structure that contains a single union member.

documentation: A REST JSON service that sends JSON requests and responses.
